nited States)|21st Signal Brigade's]] 55th Signal Company</center>\nFile:US Army 982nd Signal Company Flash.png|<center>[[335th Theater Signal Command (United States)|359th Signal Brigade's]] 982nd Signal Company</center>\nFile:US Army 112th SIG BN Flash.svg|<center>[[528th Sustainment Brigade (United States)|528th Sustainment Brigade's]] [[112th Special Operations Signal Battalion]]</center>\n</gallery>\n\n====[[Special Forces (United States Army)|Special Forces]]====\n<gallery>\nFile:US Army 1st Special Forces Command-Joint Staff Element flash.svg|<center>Special Forces personnel assigned to the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]]</center>\nFile:US Army Special Forces Personnel in non-Special Forces units flash.png|<center>Special Forces personnel in non-special operations units</center>\nFile:US Army 1st Special Forces Command Flash.png|<center>[[1st Special Forces Command (Airborne)|1st Special Forces Command]]</center>\nFile:1sfg.png|<center>[[1st Special Forces Group (United States)|1st Special Forces Group]]</center>\nFile:US Army 39th SFD Beret Flash.png|<center>1st Special Forces Group's 39th Special Forces Detachment</center>\nFile:3sfg.svg|<center>[[3rd Special Forces Group (United States)|3rd Special Forces Group]]</center>\nFile:5th SFG Beret Flash.png|<center>[[5th Special Forces Group (United States)|5th Special Forces Group]]</center>\nFile:7th Special Forces Group.svg|<center>[[7th Special Forces Group (United States)|7th Special Forces Group]]</center>\nFile:USA - 10th Special Forces Flash.svg|<center>[[10th Special Forces Group (United States)|10th Special Forces Group]]</center>\nFile:19sfg.png|<center>[[19th Special Forces Group (United States)|19th Special Forces Group]]</center>\nFile:20th Special Forces Group flash.png|<center>[[20th Special Forces Group (United States)|20th Special Forces Group]]</center>\n</gallery>\n\n====Support====\n<gallery>\nFile:US Army 725th Bde Support Bn Flash.png|<center>[[25th Infantry Division (United States)|25th Infantry Division]], [[4th Brigade Combat Team (Airborne), 25th Infantry Division|4th Infantry Brigade Combat Team's]] [[725th Support Battalion (United States)|725th Brigade Support Battalion]]</center>\nFile:US Army 307th Bde Support BN Flash.svg|<center>[[82nd Airborne Division]], 1st Infantry Brigade Combat Team's 307th Brigade Support Battalion</center>\nFile:US Army 407th Bde Support BN Flash.svg|<center>82nd Airborne Division, 2nd Infantry Brigade Combat Team's [[407th Forward Support Battalion|407th Brigade Support Battalion]]</center>\nFile:US Army 82nd Bde Support BN Flash.png|<center>82nd Airborne Division, 3rd Infantry Brigade Combat Team's [[82nd Brigade Support Battalion]]</center>\nFile:US Army 122nd Aviation Support Bn Flash.svg|<center>82nd Airborne Division, Combat Aviation Brigade's 122nd Aviation Support Battalion</center>\nFile:US Army 173rd Bde Support BN Flash.png|<center>[[173rd Airborne Brigade Combat Team|173rd Airborne Brigade's]] [[173rd Support Battalion (United States)|173rd Brigade Support Battalion]]</center>\n</gallery>\n\n====[[Sustainment Brigades in the United States Army|Sustainment]]====\n<gallery>\nFile:US Army 82nd Sustainment Brigade Flash.png|<center>[[82nd Sustainment Brigade]]</center>\nFile:US Army 528th Support Battalion Flash.png|<center>[[528th Sustainment Brigade (United States)|528th Sustainment Brigade (Special Operations)]]</center> \n</gallery>\n\n====Training====\n<gallery>\nFile:US Army Airborne and Ranger Training Bde Flash.svg|<center>[[United States Army Infantry School|Airborne and Ranger Training Brigade]]</center>\nFile:US Army 1st BN-507th Inf Reg Flash.png|<center>Airborne and Ranger Training Brigade's [[507th Parachute Infantry Regiment (United States)|507th Infantry Regiment]], 1st Battalion</center>\nFile:US Army JRTC Flash.png|<center>[[Fort Polk|Joint Readiness Training Center]] (JRTC)-Army Element</center>\nFile:US Army 1st Bn-509th Inf Reg Flash.png|<center>JRTC's [[509th Infantry Regiment (United States)|509th Infantry Regiment]], 1st Battalion</center>\nFile:US Army JROTC Flash.png|<center>[[Junior Reserve Officers' Training Corps]]</center>\nFile:US Army C Company, 262nd Quartermaster Battalion Flash.png|<center>[[Quartermaster Center and School]]'s 262nd Quartermaster Battalion</center>\nFile:Security Force Assistance Command Flash.svg|<center>[[Security Force Assistance Command]] (SFAC)</center>\nFile:1st Security Force Assistance Brigade Flash.svg|<center>SFAC's [[1st Security Force Assistance Brigade]]</center>\nFile:US Army 2nd Security Force Assistance Brigade Flash.svg|<center>SFAC's [[2nd Security Force Assistance Brigade]]</center>\nFile:US Army 3rd Security Force Assistance Brigade Flash.svg|<center>SFAC's [[3rd Security Force Assistance Brigade]]</center>\nFile:US Army 4th Security Force Assistance Brigade Beret Flash.svg|<center>SFAC's 4th Security Force Assistance Brigade</center>\nFile:US Army 5th Security Force Assistance Brigade Beret Flash.svg|<center>SFAC's 5th Security Force Assistance Brigade</center>\nFile:US Army 54th Security Force Assistance Brigade Beret Flash.svg|<center>SFAC's 54th Security Force Assistance Brigade</center>\nFile:USAJFKSWCS flash.gif|<center>[[John F. Kennedy Special Warfare Center and School|US Army John F. Kennedy Special Warfare Center and School]] (SWCS)</center>\nFile:US Army Special Forces Warrant Officer Institute Flash.png|<center>SWCS's Special Forces Warrant Officer Institute</center>\nFile:US Army Special Warfare Education Group Flash.png|<center>SWCS's Special Warfare Education Group</center>\nFile:US Army Special Warfare Medical Group Flash.png|<center>SWCS's Special Warfare Medical Group</center>\nFile:US Army Special Warfare NCO Academy Flash.png|<center>SWCS's Special Warfare [[Non-Commissioned Officer]] Academy</center>\nFile:US Army Special Warfare Training Group Flash.png|<center>SWCS's 1st Special Warfare Training Group</center>\nFile:US Army 18th Airborne Corps NCO Academy Flash.png|<center>[[XVIII Airborne Corps]]'s [[Enlisted Professional Military Education|Non-Commissioned Officer Academy]]</center>\nFile:US Army Advanced Airborne School Flash.png|<center>[[82nd Airborne Division]]'s [[United States Army Jumpmaster School|Advanced Airborne School]]</center>\n</gallery>\n\n===US Air Force===\n<gallery>\nFile:USAF Combat Aviation Advisor flash.svg|<center>Combat Aviation Advisor ([[6th Special Operations Squadron]] (SOS) and [[711th Special Operations Squadron|711th SOS]])</center>\nFile:USAF Combat Controller Flash.jpg|<center>[[United States Air Force Combat Control Team|Combat Controller]]</center>\nFile:USAF Combat Rescue Officer Flash.png|<center>[[Combat rescue officer|Combat Rescue Officer]]</center>\nFile:USAF Pararescue Flash.jpg|<center>[[Pararescueman]]</center>\nFile:USAF Security Forces beret flash.jpg|<center>[[United States Air Force Security Forces|Security Forces]]</center>\nFile:USAF Security Forces flash-Officer.png|<center>Security Forces Officer</center>\nFile:USAF Special Reconnaissance Flash.png|<center>[[United States Air Force Special Reconnaissance|Special Reconnaissance]]</center>\nFile:USAF Special Tactics Officer Flash.png|<center>[[United States Air Force Special Tactics Officer|Special Tactics Officer]]</center>\nFile:USAF SERE Flash.jpg|<center>[[Survival, Evasion, Resistance and Escape]] Instructor</center>\nFile:USAF Tactical Air Control Party Beret Flash.svg|<center>[[United States Air Force Tactical Air Control Party|Tactical Air Control Party]]</center>\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Obsolete badges of the United States military]]\n* [[Badges of the United States Air Force]]\n* [[Uniforms of the United States Air Force]]\n* [[Uniforms of the United States Navy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{US Army uniforms}}\n{{US Army navbox}}\n{{US Air Force navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:United States Military Beret Flash}}\n[[Category:Heraldry of the United States Army]]\n", "name_user": "McChizzle", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Minor image format edits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_military_beret_flash"}
{"title_page": "Peeps", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Peep (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox Brand\n|logo=\n|name=Peeps\n|image=[[Image:Peeps-Yellow-Pink.jpg|250px|Yellow and pink Peeps]]\n|type=[[Confectionery]]\n|currentowner=[[Just Born]]\n|origin=[[United States]]\n|introduced=1953\n|discontinued= \n|related= \n|markets= \n|previousowners=''Rodda Candy Company''\n|trademarkregistrations= \n|website=[https://www.marshmallowpeeps.com www.marshmallowpeeps.com]\n}}\n\n'''Peeps''' are [[marshmallow]]s sold in the United States and Canada that are shaped into ducks, bunnies, and other animals. There are also different shapes used for various [[holidays]]. Peeps are used primarily to fill [[Easter baskets]], though recent{{recently|date=September 2015}} advertising campaigns market the candy as \"Peeps - Always in Season\", as Peeps has since expanded to include [[Halloween]], [[Christmas]] and [[Valentine's Day]]; since 2014 it has been available year-round with the introduction of Peeps Minis. They are made from sugar, corn syrup, gelatin, various food dyes and pinch of salt.\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Candy eggs in an Easter basket.JPG|thumb|left|Peeps bunnies in an Easter basket]]\n\nPeeps are produced by [[Just Born]],<ref>{{cite web |author=Lehner, Marla |title=The Power of Peeps |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,84455,00.html |work=[[Fox News]] |date=2003-04-17 |accessdate=2009-04-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305185448/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0%2C2933%2C84455%2C00.html |archivedate=2009-03-05 }}</ref> a candy manufacturer founded in [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania|Bethlehem]], [[Pennsylvania]], by Russian immigrant [[Sam Born]] (1891-1959).  In 1953 Just Born acquired the Rodda Candy Company and its marshmallow chick line, and replaced the painstaking process of hand-forming the chicks with mass production.<ref>{{cite news|title=Peeps: A candy and a technological wonder |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/2003-04-16-peeps_x.htm |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=2003-04-16 |accessdate=2009-04-22 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401094214/http://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/2003-04-16-peeps_x.htm |archivedate=2010-04-01 }}</ref> When founder Sam Born would display a sign for his freshly made candy, he would title it \"Just Born\", playing off of his last name and the fact that he made his candy fresh daily.<ref>\"Fun Facts About Just Born Candies\". Fun Facts About Just Born Candies. N.p., n.d. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://www.justborn.com/just-for-fun/fun-facts {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140128153913/http://www.justborn.com/just-for-fun/fun-facts |date=2014-01-28 }}>.</ref> According to Mary Bellis, the newly purchased company, Just Born, was soon the \"largest marshmallow candy manufacturer in the world.\" New shapes other than the chicks were produced following a theme according to the season starting in the 1960s. 20 years later, the Marshmallow Peeps Bunny was released as a popular year round shape of the candy.<ref>Bellis, Mary. \"The History of Marshmallow Peeps.\" About.com Inventors. N.p., n.d. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://inventors.about.com/od/foodrelatedinventions/a/marshmallows_2.htm>.</ref> The yellow chicks were the original form of the candy&nbsp;\u2014 hence their name&nbsp;\u2014 but then the company introduced other colors and, eventually, the myriad shapes in which they are now produced. Peeps were manufactured in different colors such as lavender and blue starting in 1995. Prior to that they were only being produced in the traditional colors: yellow, pink and white. New flavors such as vanilla, strawberry, and chocolate were introduced between the years of 1999 and 2002.<ref>Bellis, Mary. \"The History of Marshmallow Peeps.\" About.com Inventors. N.p., n.d. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://inventors.about.com/od/foodrelatedinventions/a/marshmallows_2.htm>.</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Just Born expanded the Peeps product line  further by introducing Peeps Lip Balm in four flavors: grape, strawberry, vanilla, and cotton candy.<ref>{{cite journal\n |author=Zimmer, Erin \n |title=Peeps Lip Balm, Reviewed \n |date=April 2, 2009 \n |url=http://www.seriouseats.com/2009/04/peeps-lip-balm-reviewed.html \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090405062416/http://www.seriouseats.com/2009/04/peeps-lip-balm-reviewed.html \n |archivedate=April 5, 2009 \n}}</ref> Just Born has come out with several other various accessories. Items such as nail polish, wrist bands, umbrellas, plush toys, golf gloves, earrings, and necklaces are produced and sold online and in retail stores. Other companies have produced items based on the popular Peeps candy. Peeps micro bead pillows were made by Kaboodle and conform to one's shape. The company Kaboodle promises that \"they'll last a lot longer than their edible counterpart!\"<ref>\"Large Peeps\u00ae Microbead Pillows.\" Kaboodle. N.p., n.d. Web. 10 Nov. 2013. <http://www.kaboodle.com/reviews/large-peeps-microbead-pillows {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109193534/http://www.kaboodle.com/reviews/large-peeps-microbead-pillows |date=2014-01-09 }}>.</ref> Ranging from infant sizes to adult sizes, Peeps Halloween costumes can also be found on the shelves of several costume stores. The first Peeps & Co. store opened in November 2009 in National Harbor, Maryland, [[Prince George's County]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Mui, Ylan Q. |title=Peeps Are Hopping to Their Own Store at National Harbor |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/08/AR2009070803978.html?hpid=artslot |work=WashingtonPost.com |date=July 9, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112053013/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/08/AR2009070803978.html?hpid=artslot |archivedate=November 12, 2012 }}</ref> Peeps & Company retail stores were later opened in Minnesota (As of 2019 shut down due to low profits) and Pennsylvania.<ref>\"The History of Peeps.\" Fox News. FOX News Network, 8 Mar. 2013. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2013/03/08/history-peeps/>.</ref> In 2014, Peeps Minis were introduced, and were intended to be available year-round.\n<!--[Commented out for lack of reliable references/notability]\n\n==Seasonal Products==\n{{advert|section|date=April 2015}}\nPeeps released special flavored Peeps depending on the holiday/season. In the summer, lemonade and bubblegum-flavored Marshmallow Chicks are manufactured. For Valentine\u2019s Day, Peeps produces a variety of marshmallow treats such as Chocolate Dipped Strawberry Cr\u00e8me Flavored Chicks, Chocolate Mousse Flavored Marshmallow Bears, and Chocolate Covered Raspberry Flavored Heart. Come Easter, all the original Marshmallow Bunnies and Chicks are released as well as other ones such as Chocolate Mousse Flavored Bunnies and Chocolate Dipped Marshmallow Chicks. During Halloween, no Marshmallow Bunnies are released; however, Chocolate-Dipped Orange Chicks, Marshmallow Pumpkins, Marshmallow Ghosts, Chocolate Mousse Flavored Cats, and Snack-Size Marshmallow Chicks are put on shelves for sale. A new release as of 2013, the Snack-Size Marshmallow Chicks are intended for passing out to trick-or-treaters on [[Halloween]] and come in various colors including purple, green, and orange. With Christmas brings several different flavors and colors. Chocolate-Dipped Candy Cane Flavored Marshmallow Chicks, Chocolate-Dipped Sugar Cookie Flavored Marshmallow Chicks, Chocolate-Dipped Caramel Flavored Marshmallow Chicks, and Gingerbread Flavored Marshmallow Gingerbread Men are all released specially flavored to the [[Christmas]] theme. Different shapes including Marshmallow Candy Cane Flavored Stars, Marshmallow Reindeer, Marshmallow Christmas Trees, and Marshmallow Snowmen are also produced.<ref>\"BROWSE OUR SHOW & SHARE GALLERY!\" Peeps. N.p., n.d. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://www.marshmallowpeeps.com/product-detail/halloween/snack-size-marshmallow-chicks>.</ref>\n\n[End of comment-out]-->\n\n==Contests and competitions==\n\n[[Image:Orange peeps.jpg|right|thumb|Orange pumpkin [[Halloween]] Peeps]]\nAn annual \"Peeps Eating\" contest is held each year at [[National Harbor]] in front of the Peeps & Company store.<ref name=\"patch\">{{cite web|url=http://patch.com/virginia/oldtownalexandria/world-peeps-eating-contest-saturday-national-harbor |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-02-13 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214103358/http://patch.com/virginia/oldtownalexandria/world-peeps-eating-contest-saturday-national-harbor |archivedate=2017-02-14 }}</ref> 2017 winner, [[Matt Stonie]] of California, ate 255 Peeps in five minutes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reiss |first1=Jaclyn |title=This man ate a record 255 Peeps in 5 minutes - The Boston Globe |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2017/04/09/this-man-ate-record-peeps-minutes/xNd2fmr8sh2H8qz8d1IxlJ/story.html |accessdate=13 April 2017 |work=BostonGlobe.com |date=10 April 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516155837/https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2017/04/09/this-man-ate-record-peeps-minutes/xNd2fmr8sh2H8qz8d1IxlJ/story.html |archivedate=16 May 2017 }}</ref> The first such event was arranged by Shawn Sparks in 1994, and had only six participants.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://peep.peril.org/peepoff.html |title=The unofficial Marshmallow Peep page |accessdate=2007-07-09 |author=Jack Eidsness |date=April 1996 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070617052855/http://peep.peril.org/peepoff.html |archive-date=2007-06-17 |url-status=dead }}{{dubious|date=November 2010}}</ref> Dave Smith started an annual Peep Off in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] after contacting a participant in the first Peep Off.<ref>{{cite news\n |author=Vincent P. Bzdek \n |title=50 years of turning Easter into one big Peeps show \n |url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4176/is_20040411/ai_n14573992/print\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071102220644/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4176/is_20040411/ai_n14573992/print\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=2 November 2007\n |publisher=Oakland Tribune (reprinted from [Washington Post article]) \n |date=11 April 2004 \n |accessdate=2007-08-09 \n}}</ref><ref>[https://articles.latimes.com/2009/dec/11/nation/la-na-peeps11-2009dec11 First Peeps store is a mecca for all their 'peeple'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430140315/http://articles.latimes.com/2009/dec/11/nation/la-na-peeps11-2009dec11 |date=2011-04-30 }}, ''Los Angeles Times'', December 11, 2009</ref> Another contest in Maryland asks that participants create a diorama of a culturally important scene from the modern era, featuring a number of Peeps. The winner gets two free inflatable life jackets.<ref>\"Peeps Madness | Bay Weekly.\" Peeps Madness | Bay Weekly. N.p., n.d. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://bayweekly.com/articles/creature-feature/article/peeps-madness>.</ref>\n\nSeveral newspapers hold annual contests in which readers submit photos of dioramas featuring Peeps.  The ''[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]'' was the first paper to hold such a contest.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}} Similar contests are put on by The ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', and the ''[[Seattle Times]]''. These contests frequently correspond with the [[Easter]] holiday. MIT also has a yearly Peeps contest. <ref>[http://alum.mit.edu/pages/sliceofmit/2010/05/18/peeps/ Alum.mit.edu] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129113022/http://alum.mit.edu/pages/sliceofmit/2010/05/18/peeps/ |date=2010-11-29 }}</ref> The [[The Washington Post|Washington Post]] held an annual contest until 2017, when it was discontinued. The smaller [[Washington City Paper]] introduced their contest in it place.\n\nThe Racine Art Museum is sponsoring the International Peeps Competition from April 1\u201328. Anyone can enter the contest, centered on the theme \"peep-powered work of art\".<ref>[http://www.zagat.com/buzz/its-peeps-art-time Zagat Buzz Blog: It's Peeps Art Time! March 22, 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110325141410/http://www.zagat.com/buzz/its-peeps-art-time |date=March 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe following are other contests held in various states. Peeps [[jousting]] consists of putting two Marshmallow Chicks into the microwave and seeing which one gets the biggest and therefore affects/deforms the other. \"Peepza\" is a dessert pizza made with Peeps. Also, blogs were created according to Fox News entitled \"101 Fun Ways to Torture a Peep.\"<ref>\"The History of Peeps.\" Fox News. FOX News Network, 8 Mar. 2013. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2013/03/08/history-peeps/>.</ref>\n\n==Alleged indestructibility==\n\nPeeps are sometimes jokingly described as \"indestructible\". In 1999 scientists at [[Emory University]] jokingly<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emory.edu/EMORY_REPORT/erarchive/1999/March/ermarch.29/3_29_99peeps.html |title=Emory pair unlocks the mystery of Peeps |publisher=[[Emory University]] |work=Emory Report |date=1999-03-29 |accessdate=2012-07-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403052129/http://www.emory.edu/EMORY_REPORT/erarchive/1999/March/ermarch.29/3_29_99peeps.html |archivedate=2013-04-03 }}</ref> performed experiments on batches of Peeps to see how easily they could be dissolved, burned or otherwise disintegrated, using such agents as cigarette smoke, boiling water and liquid nitrogen.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/default/article/Peeps-Rule-Roost-Easter-s-unofficial-2938583.php |title=Peeps Rule Roost / Easter's unofficial marshmallow treat now a chic and easy target to spoof |last=Severson |first=Kim |date=April 3, 1999 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=2013-03-04 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506144628/http://www.sfgate.com/default/article/Peeps-Rule-Roost-Easter-s-unofficial-2938583.php |archivedate=May 6, 2013 }}</ref> In addition to discussing whether Peeps migrate or evolve, they claimed that the eyes of the confectionery \"wouldn't dissolve in anything\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/culture/articles/991011/archive_002077.htm |title=What Do You Call a Guy Who Cuts Apart Peeps? |date=October 3, 1999 |work=U S News |accessdate=2009-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413144504/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/culture/articles/991011/archive_002077.htm |archivedate=April 13, 2009 }}</ref> One website claims that Peeps are [[insoluble]] in [[acetone]], water, diluted [[sulfuric acid]], and [[sodium hydroxide]] (the site also claims that the Peeps experimental subjects sign release forms).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peepresearch.org/solubility.html |title=solubility |publisher=Peepresearch.org |accessdate=2010-10-25 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126065219/http://peepresearch.org/solubility.html |archivedate=2010-11-26 }}</ref> Concentrated [[sulfuric acid]] seems to have effects similar to the expected effects of sulfuric acid on sugar.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://students.millikin.edu/~acs/HTML/peep_revenge.html |title= Peep Wars: Revenge of the Mole |publisher= Students.millikin.edu |date= 2005-10-23 |accessdate= 2010-10-25}}</ref>\n\nThis debate featured in an episode of the [[sitcom]] ''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]'' (\"Traffic Jam\"), in which [[Francis (Malcolm in the Middle)|Francis]], insisting the \"Quacks\" (as they were called) would dissolve in his stomach rather than expand, takes up the dare to eat 100 of them and does so, but gets very sick in the process.\n\nAs marshmallow ages exposed to air \u2014 it dehydrates, becoming \"stale\" and slightly crunchy. According to Just Born, 25%-30% of their customers prefer eating Peeps stale.<ref>\n{{cite web\n |last1=Bratskeir \n |first1=Kate \n |title=Here Are The Answers To Every Question You've Never Asked About Marshmallow Peeps \n |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/18/marshmallow-peeps-easter-facts_n_5147153.html \n |website=Huffington Post \n |accessdate=8 July 2014 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716052724/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/18/marshmallow-peeps-easter-facts_n_5147153.html \n |archivedate=16 July 2014 \n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Public relations==\n[[Barry Church]], a football player for the Dallas Cowboys, was unable to attend training camp due to an unexpected root canal. Peeps offered Church a season's supply of their product\u2014in that marshmallows are a lot softer on the teeth than the Jolly Ranchers which caused Church's requirement of a root canal.<ref>\"Barry Church Gets Candy Offer.\" News. N.p., 1 Aug. 2013. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://www.marshmallowpeeps.com/news {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109190551/http://www.marshmallowpeeps.com/news |date=2014-01-09 }}>.</ref>\n\n==Recipes using Peeps==\n[[File:Coconut cake garnished with Peeps candy.jpg|thumb|A [[coconut cake]] garnished with Peeps candy]]\nSeveral recipes and creative ideas to alter Peeps have been invented. ''Fox News Magazine'' published an article in 2013 including several recipes from various creators, including Peeps [[smore]]s, Peeps [[pancake]]s, home-made chocolate covered Peeps, Peeps marshmallow chocolate chip cookies, Peeps [[Chocolate brownie|brownies]], Peeps [[popcorn]], Peeps [[Icing (food)|frosting]], Peeps Krispie [[Treats]], and Peeps [[syrup]].<ref>\"8 Recipes To Make With Peeps This Easter\". ''Fox News Magazine''. N.p., 26 Mar. 2013. Web. 10 Nov. 2013. <http://magazine.foxnews.com/food-wellness/8-easter-recipes-call-peeps {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109191203/http://magazine.foxnews.com/food-wellness/8-easter-recipes-call-peeps |date=2014-01-09 }}>.</ref>\n\nPeeps can also be used as a marshmallow topper for hot chocolate. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://foodchannel.com/recipes/homemade-hot-cocoa-marshmallow-peeps|title=Homemade Hot Cocoa with PEEPS\u00ae|date=2016-03-17|work=Food Channel|access-date=2018-04-02|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403051955/https://foodchannel.com/recipes/homemade-hot-cocoa-marshmallow-peeps|archive-date=2018-04-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nA recipe for \"Peepshi\" involves placing a Peep onto a [[Rice Krispie]] Treat and wrapping it in a [[Fruit by the Foot]], to create a single \"Peepshi roll\" in the style of a [[Sushi|sushi roll]].<ref>Kang, Grace. \"Serious Eats - Seriouseats.com.\" Serious Eats. N.p., 31 Mar. 2010. Web. 10 Nov. 2013. <http://www.seriouseats.com/recipes/2010/03/peeps-recipes-how-to-make-peepshi-sushi-rice-krispies-treats-easter.html>.</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, several internet and [[Twitter]] postings, and TV news stories claimed 'outrage' that Peeps were being used as a pizza topping.<ref>http://www.reviewed.com/home-outdoors/news/someone-put-peeps-on-pizza-and-the-internet-is-freaking-out  {{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2017/04/05/the-internet-is-losing-it-over-peepza-peeps-on-a-pizza/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-04-06 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521172431/http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2017/04/05/the-internet-is-losing-it-over-peepza-peeps-on-a-pizza/ |archivedate=2017-05-21 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*On April 22, 2014 [[Adam Rifkin]] acquired the feature film and TV rights to the classic candies to make a franchise of it.<ref>{{cite news|title=Adam Rifkin Eyes 'Peeps' Classic Candy Treats For Animated Film & TV Franchise |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/04/peeps-candy-movie-tv-adam-rifkin/ |accessdate=23 April 2014 |newspaper=deadline.com |date=22 April 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425200540/http://www.deadline.com/2014/04/peeps-candy-movie-tv-adam-rifkin/ |archivedate=25 April 2014 }}</ref>\n*In the 2000 Fox TV show ''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]'' episode \"Traffic Jam\", the candy is known as Quacks and of which Francis attempts to eat 100 of them to prove a skeptical cadet wrong, but ends up getting sick from it.\n*In the 2007 Comedy Central TV show ''[[South Park]]'' episode \"Fantastic Easter Special\", a man named Professor Teabag (who knows of an Easter conspiracy) helps [[Stan Marsh]] and [[Kyle Broflovski]] escape from some ninjas by putting Peeps in the microwave, causing an explosion that destroys the mansion and killing both him and the ninjas.\n*In 2007-2008, Peeps featured prominently in the [[Vlogbrothers]] video blog series, primarily serving as comedic fodder for [https://nerdfighteria.info/article/1491 punishments].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of confectionery brands]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n*[http://www.marshmallowpeeps.com/ Peeps Official Website]\n*[http://www.marshmallowpeeps.org/pcn.html Tour of the Peeps Factory]\n*[http://www.peepresearch.org Peep Research]\n*[http://www.magnet.fsu.edu/education/community/slideshows/belljar/index.html How Atmospheric Pressure Affects Objects]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (audio slideshow, featuring Peeps, from the National High Magnetic Field Laboratory)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180805013919/http://powerofthepeep.com/ Peeps Documentary]\n*[http://www.salon.com/food/eyewitness_cook/index.html?story=/food/francis_lam/2010/04/03/toasted_peeps_brulee_recipe Peeps br\u00fbl\u00e9e! Like toasted marshmallows, but awesomer], Salon.com\n*[http://www.slate.com/id/2098422 Why Eat Peeps at Easter? How the marshmallow chicks found Jesus.], Slate.com\n\n{{Just Born}}\n\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1953]]\n[[Category:Brand name confectionery]]\n[[Category:Easter food]]\n[[Category:Just Born brands]]\n[[Category:Marshmallows]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Peep (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox Brand\n|logo=\n|name=Peeps\n|image=[[Image:Peeps-Yellow-Pink.jpg|250px|Yellow and pink Peeps]]\n|type=[[Confectionery]]\n|currentowner=[[Just Born]]\n|origin=[[United States]]\n|introduced=1953\n|discontinued= \n|related= \n|markets= \n|previousowners=''Rodda Candy Company''\n|trademarkregistrations= \n|website=[https://www.marshmallowpeeps.com www.marshmallowpeeps.com]\n}}\n\n'''Peeps''' are [[marshmallow]]s sold in the United States and Canada that are shaped into chicks, bunnies, and other animals. There are also different shapes used for various [[holidays]]. Peeps are used primarily to fill [[Easter baskets]], though recent{{recently|date=September 2015}} advertising campaigns market the candy as \"Peeps - Always in Season\", as Peeps has since expanded to include [[Halloween]], [[Christmas]] and [[Valentine's Day]]; since 2014 it has been available year-round with the introduction of Peeps Minis. They are made from sugar, corn syrup, gelatin, various food dyes and pinch of salt.\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Candy eggs in an Easter basket.JPG|thumb|left|Peeps bunnies in an Easter basket]]\n\nPeeps are produced by [[Just Born]],<ref>{{cite web |author=Lehner, Marla |title=The Power of Peeps |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,84455,00.html |work=[[Fox News]] |date=2003-04-17 |accessdate=2009-04-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305185448/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0%2C2933%2C84455%2C00.html |archivedate=2009-03-05 }}</ref> a candy manufacturer founded in [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania|Bethlehem]], [[Pennsylvania]], by Russian immigrant [[Sam Born]] (1891-1959).  In 1953 Just Born acquired the Rodda Candy Company and its marshmallow chick line, and replaced the painstaking process of hand-forming the chicks with mass production.<ref>{{cite news|title=Peeps: A candy and a technological wonder |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/2003-04-16-peeps_x.htm |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=2003-04-16 |accessdate=2009-04-22 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401094214/http://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/2003-04-16-peeps_x.htm |archivedate=2010-04-01 }}</ref> When founder Sam Born would display a sign for his freshly made candy, he would title it \"Just Born\", playing off of his last name and the fact that he made his candy fresh daily.<ref>\"Fun Facts About Just Born Candies\". Fun Facts About Just Born Candies. N.p., n.d. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://www.justborn.com/just-for-fun/fun-facts {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140128153913/http://www.justborn.com/just-for-fun/fun-facts |date=2014-01-28 }}>.</ref> According to Mary Bellis, the newly purchased company, Just Born, was soon the \"largest marshmallow candy manufacturer in the world.\" New shapes other than the chicks were produced following a theme according to the season starting in the 1960s. 20 years later, the Marshmallow Peeps Bunny was released as a popular year round shape of the candy.<ref>Bellis, Mary. \"The History of Marshmallow Peeps.\" About.com Inventors. N.p., n.d. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://inventors.about.com/od/foodrelatedinventions/a/marshmallows_2.htm>.</ref> The yellow chicks were the original form of the candy&nbsp;\u2014 hence their name&nbsp;\u2014 but then the company introduced other colors and, eventually, the myriad shapes in which they are now produced. Peeps were manufactured in different colors such as lavender and blue starting in 1995. Prior to that they were only being produced in the traditional colors: yellow, pink and white. New flavors such as vanilla, strawberry, and chocolate were introduced between the years of 1999 and 2002.<ref>Bellis, Mary. \"The History of Marshmallow Peeps.\" About.com Inventors. N.p., n.d. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://inventors.about.com/od/foodrelatedinventions/a/marshmallows_2.htm>.</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Just Born expanded the Peeps product line  further by introducing Peeps Lip Balm in four flavors: grape, strawberry, vanilla, and cotton candy.<ref>{{cite journal\n |author=Zimmer, Erin \n |title=Peeps Lip Balm, Reviewed \n |date=April 2, 2009 \n |url=http://www.seriouseats.com/2009/04/peeps-lip-balm-reviewed.html \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090405062416/http://www.seriouseats.com/2009/04/peeps-lip-balm-reviewed.html \n |archivedate=April 5, 2009 \n}}</ref> Just Born has come out with several other various accessories. Items such as nail polish, wrist bands, umbrellas, plush toys, golf gloves, earrings, and necklaces are produced and sold online and in retail stores. Other companies have produced items based on the popular Peeps candy. Peeps micro bead pillows were made by Kaboodle and conform to one's shape. The company Kaboodle promises that \"they'll last a lot longer than their edible counterpart!\"<ref>\"Large Peeps\u00ae Microbead Pillows.\" Kaboodle. N.p., n.d. Web. 10 Nov. 2013. <http://www.kaboodle.com/reviews/large-peeps-microbead-pillows {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109193534/http://www.kaboodle.com/reviews/large-peeps-microbead-pillows |date=2014-01-09 }}>.</ref> Ranging from infant sizes to adult sizes, Peeps Halloween costumes can also be found on the shelves of several costume stores. The first Peeps & Co. store opened in November 2009 in National Harbor, Maryland, [[Prince George's County]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Mui, Ylan Q. |title=Peeps Are Hopping to Their Own Store at National Harbor |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/08/AR2009070803978.html?hpid=artslot |work=WashingtonPost.com |date=July 9, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112053013/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/08/AR2009070803978.html?hpid=artslot |archivedate=November 12, 2012 }}</ref> Peeps & Company retail stores were later opened in Minnesota (As of 2019 shut down due to low profits) and Pennsylvania.<ref>\"The History of Peeps.\" Fox News. FOX News Network, 8 Mar. 2013. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2013/03/08/history-peeps/>.</ref> In 2014, Peeps Minis were introduced, and were intended to be available year-round.\n<!--[Commented out for lack of reliable references/notability]\n\n==Seasonal Products==\n{{advert|section|date=April 2015}}\nPeeps released special flavored Peeps depending on the holiday/season. In the summer, lemonade and bubblegum-flavored Marshmallow Chicks are manufactured. For Valentine\u2019s Day, Peeps produces a variety of marshmallow treats such as Chocolate Dipped Strawberry Cr\u00e8me Flavored Chicks, Chocolate Mousse Flavored Marshmallow Bears, and Chocolate Covered Raspberry Flavored Heart. Come Easter, all the original Marshmallow Bunnies and Chicks are released as well as other ones such as Chocolate Mousse Flavored Bunnies and Chocolate Dipped Marshmallow Chicks. During Halloween, no Marshmallow Bunnies are released; however, Chocolate-Dipped Orange Chicks, Marshmallow Pumpkins, Marshmallow Ghosts, Chocolate Mousse Flavored Cats, and Snack-Size Marshmallow Chicks are put on shelves for sale. A new release as of 2013, the Snack-Size Marshmallow Chicks are intended for passing out to trick-or-treaters on [[Halloween]] and come in various colors including purple, green, and orange. With Christmas brings several different flavors and colors. Chocolate-Dipped Candy Cane Flavored Marshmallow Chicks, Chocolate-Dipped Sugar Cookie Flavored Marshmallow Chicks, Chocolate-Dipped Caramel Flavored Marshmallow Chicks, and Gingerbread Flavored Marshmallow Gingerbread Men are all released specially flavored to the [[Christmas]] theme. Different shapes including Marshmallow Candy Cane Flavored Stars, Marshmallow Reindeer, Marshmallow Christmas Trees, and Marshmallow Snowmen are also produced.<ref>\"BROWSE OUR SHOW & SHARE GALLERY!\" Peeps. N.p., n.d. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://www.marshmallowpeeps.com/product-detail/halloween/snack-size-marshmallow-chicks>.</ref>\n\n[End of comment-out]-->\n\n==Contests and competitions==\n\n[[Image:Orange peeps.jpg|right|thumb|Orange pumpkin [[Halloween]] Peeps]]\nAn annual \"Peeps Eating\" contest is held each year at [[National Harbor]] in front of the Peeps & Company store.<ref name=\"patch\">{{cite web|url=http://patch.com/virginia/oldtownalexandria/world-peeps-eating-contest-saturday-national-harbor |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-02-13 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214103358/http://patch.com/virginia/oldtownalexandria/world-peeps-eating-contest-saturday-national-harbor |archivedate=2017-02-14 }}</ref> 2017 winner, [[Matt Stonie]] of California, ate 255 Peeps in five minutes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reiss |first1=Jaclyn |title=This man ate a record 255 Peeps in 5 minutes - The Boston Globe |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2017/04/09/this-man-ate-record-peeps-minutes/xNd2fmr8sh2H8qz8d1IxlJ/story.html |accessdate=13 April 2017 |work=BostonGlobe.com |date=10 April 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516155837/https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2017/04/09/this-man-ate-record-peeps-minutes/xNd2fmr8sh2H8qz8d1IxlJ/story.html |archivedate=16 May 2017 }}</ref> The first such event was arranged by Shawn Sparks in 1994, and had only six participants.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://peep.peril.org/peepoff.html |title=The unofficial Marshmallow Peep page |accessdate=2007-07-09 |author=Jack Eidsness |date=April 1996 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070617052855/http://peep.peril.org/peepoff.html |archive-date=2007-06-17 |url-status=dead }}{{dubious|date=November 2010}}</ref> Dave Smith started an annual Peep Off in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] after contacting a participant in the first Peep Off.<ref>{{cite news\n |author=Vincent P. Bzdek \n |title=50 years of turning Easter into one big Peeps show \n |url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4176/is_20040411/ai_n14573992/print\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071102220644/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4176/is_20040411/ai_n14573992/print\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=2 November 2007\n |publisher=Oakland Tribune (reprinted from [Washington Post article]) \n |date=11 April 2004 \n |accessdate=2007-08-09 \n}}</ref><ref>[https://articles.latimes.com/2009/dec/11/nation/la-na-peeps11-2009dec11 First Peeps store is a mecca for all their 'peeple'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430140315/http://articles.latimes.com/2009/dec/11/nation/la-na-peeps11-2009dec11 |date=2011-04-30 }}, ''Los Angeles Times'', December 11, 2009</ref> Another contest in Maryland asks that participants create a diorama of a culturally important scene from the modern era, featuring a number of Peeps. The winner gets two free inflatable life jackets.<ref>\"Peeps Madness | Bay Weekly.\" Peeps Madness | Bay Weekly. N.p., n.d. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://bayweekly.com/articles/creature-feature/article/peeps-madness>.</ref>\n\nSeveral newspapers hold annual contests in which readers submit photos of dioramas featuring Peeps.  The ''[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]'' was the first paper to hold such a contest.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}} Similar contests are put on by The ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', and the ''[[Seattle Times]]''. These contests frequently correspond with the [[Easter]] holiday. MIT also has a yearly Peeps contest. <ref>[http://alum.mit.edu/pages/sliceofmit/2010/05/18/peeps/ Alum.mit.edu] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129113022/http://alum.mit.edu/pages/sliceofmit/2010/05/18/peeps/ |date=2010-11-29 }}</ref> The [[The Washington Post|Washington Post]] held an annual contest until 2017, when it was discontinued. The smaller [[Washington City Paper]] introduced their contest in it place.\n\nThe Racine Art Museum is sponsoring the International Peeps Competition from April 1\u201328. Anyone can enter the contest, centered on the theme \"peep-powered work of art\".<ref>[http://www.zagat.com/buzz/its-peeps-art-time Zagat Buzz Blog: It's Peeps Art Time! March 22, 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110325141410/http://www.zagat.com/buzz/its-peeps-art-time |date=March 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe following are other contests held in various states. Peeps [[jousting]] consists of putting two Marshmallow Chicks into the microwave and seeing which one gets the biggest and therefore affects/deforms the other. \"Peepza\" is a dessert pizza made with Peeps. Also, blogs were created according to Fox News entitled \"101 Fun Ways to Torture a Peep.\"<ref>\"The History of Peeps.\" Fox News. FOX News Network, 8 Mar. 2013. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2013/03/08/history-peeps/>.</ref>\n\n==Alleged indestructibility==\n\nPeeps are sometimes jokingly described as \"indestructible\". In 1999 scientists at [[Emory University]] jokingly<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emory.edu/EMORY_REPORT/erarchive/1999/March/ermarch.29/3_29_99peeps.html |title=Emory pair unlocks the mystery of Peeps |publisher=[[Emory University]] |work=Emory Report |date=1999-03-29 |accessdate=2012-07-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403052129/http://www.emory.edu/EMORY_REPORT/erarchive/1999/March/ermarch.29/3_29_99peeps.html |archivedate=2013-04-03 }}</ref> performed experiments on batches of Peeps to see how easily they could be dissolved, burned or otherwise disintegrated, using such agents as cigarette smoke, boiling water and liquid nitrogen.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/default/article/Peeps-Rule-Roost-Easter-s-unofficial-2938583.php |title=Peeps Rule Roost / Easter's unofficial marshmallow treat now a chic and easy target to spoof |last=Severson |first=Kim |date=April 3, 1999 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=2013-03-04 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506144628/http://www.sfgate.com/default/article/Peeps-Rule-Roost-Easter-s-unofficial-2938583.php |archivedate=May 6, 2013 }}</ref> In addition to discussing whether Peeps migrate or evolve, they claimed that the eyes of the confectionery \"wouldn't dissolve in anything\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/culture/articles/991011/archive_002077.htm |title=What Do You Call a Guy Who Cuts Apart Peeps? |date=October 3, 1999 |work=U S News |accessdate=2009-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413144504/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/culture/articles/991011/archive_002077.htm |archivedate=April 13, 2009 }}</ref> One website claims that Peeps are [[insoluble]] in [[acetone]], water, diluted [[sulfuric acid]], and [[sodium hydroxide]] (the site also claims that the Peeps experimental subjects sign release forms).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peepresearch.org/solubility.html |title=solubility |publisher=Peepresearch.org |accessdate=2010-10-25 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126065219/http://peepresearch.org/solubility.html |archivedate=2010-11-26 }}</ref> Concentrated [[sulfuric acid]] seems to have effects similar to the expected effects of sulfuric acid on sugar.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://students.millikin.edu/~acs/HTML/peep_revenge.html |title= Peep Wars: Revenge of the Mole |publisher= Students.millikin.edu |date= 2005-10-23 |accessdate= 2010-10-25}}</ref>\n\nThis debate featured in an episode of the [[sitcom]] ''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]'' (\"Traffic Jam\"), in which [[Francis (Malcolm in the Middle)|Francis]], insisting the \"Quacks\" (as they were called) would dissolve in his stomach rather than expand, takes up the dare to eat 100 of them and does so, but gets very sick in the process.\n\nAs marshmallow ages exposed to air \u2014 it dehydrates, becoming \"stale\" and slightly crunchy. According to Just Born, 25%-30% of their customers prefer eating Peeps stale.<ref>\n{{cite web\n |last1=Bratskeir \n |first1=Kate \n |title=Here Are The Answers To Every Question You've Never Asked About Marshmallow Peeps \n |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/18/marshmallow-peeps-easter-facts_n_5147153.html \n |website=Huffington Post \n |accessdate=8 July 2014 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716052724/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/18/marshmallow-peeps-easter-facts_n_5147153.html \n |archivedate=16 July 2014 \n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Public relations==\n[[Barry Church]], a football player for the Dallas Cowboys, was unable to attend training camp due to an unexpected root canal. Peeps offered Church a season's supply of their product\u2014in that marshmallows are a lot softer on the teeth than the Jolly Ranchers which caused Church's requirement of a root canal.<ref>\"Barry Church Gets Candy Offer.\" News. N.p., 1 Aug. 2013. Web. 05 Nov. 2013. <http://www.marshmallowpeeps.com/news {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109190551/http://www.marshmallowpeeps.com/news |date=2014-01-09 }}>.</ref>\n\n==Recipes using Peeps==\n[[File:Coconut cake garnished with Peeps candy.jpg|thumb|A [[coconut cake]] garnished with Peeps candy]]\nSeveral recipes and creative ideas to alter Peeps have been invented. ''Fox News Magazine'' published an article in 2013 including several recipes from various creators, including Peeps [[smore]]s, Peeps [[pancake]]s, home-made chocolate covered Peeps, Peeps marshmallow chocolate chip cookies, Peeps [[Chocolate brownie|brownies]], Peeps [[popcorn]], Peeps [[Icing (food)|frosting]], Peeps Krispie [[Treats]], and Peeps [[syrup]].<ref>\"8 Recipes To Make With Peeps This Easter\". ''Fox News Magazine''. N.p., 26 Mar. 2013. Web. 10 Nov. 2013. <http://magazine.foxnews.com/food-wellness/8-easter-recipes-call-peeps {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109191203/http://magazine.foxnews.com/food-wellness/8-easter-recipes-call-peeps |date=2014-01-09 }}>.</ref>\n\nPeeps can also be used as a marshmallow topper for hot chocolate. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://foodchannel.com/recipes/homemade-hot-cocoa-marshmallow-peeps|title=Homemade Hot Cocoa with PEEPS\u00ae|date=2016-03-17|work=Food Channel|access-date=2018-04-02|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403051955/https://foodchannel.com/recipes/homemade-hot-cocoa-marshmallow-peeps|archive-date=2018-04-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nA recipe for \"Peepshi\" involves placing a Peep onto a [[Rice Krispie]] Treat and wrapping it in a [[Fruit by the Foot]], to create a single \"Peepshi roll\" in the style of a [[Sushi|sushi roll]].<ref>Kang, Grace. \"Serious Eats - Seriouseats.com.\" Serious Eats. N.p., 31 Mar. 2010. Web. 10 Nov. 2013. <http://www.seriouseats.com/recipes/2010/03/peeps-recipes-how-to-make-peepshi-sushi-rice-krispies-treats-easter.html>.</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, several internet and [[Twitter]] postings, and TV news stories claimed 'outrage' that Peeps were being used as a pizza topping.<ref>http://www.reviewed.com/home-outdoors/news/someone-put-peeps-on-pizza-and-the-internet-is-freaking-out  {{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2017/04/05/the-internet-is-losing-it-over-peepza-peeps-on-a-pizza/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-04-06 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521172431/http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2017/04/05/the-internet-is-losing-it-over-peepza-peeps-on-a-pizza/ |archivedate=2017-05-21 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*On April 22, 2014 [[Adam Rifkin]] acquired the feature film and TV rights to the classic candies to make a franchise of it.<ref>{{cite news|title=Adam Rifkin Eyes 'Peeps' Classic Candy Treats For Animated Film & TV Franchise |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/04/peeps-candy-movie-tv-adam-rifkin/ |accessdate=23 April 2014 |newspaper=deadline.com |date=22 April 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425200540/http://www.deadline.com/2014/04/peeps-candy-movie-tv-adam-rifkin/ |archivedate=25 April 2014 }}</ref>\n*In the 2000 Fox TV show ''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]'' episode \"Traffic Jam\", the candy is known as Quacks and of which Francis attempts to eat 100 of them to prove a skeptical cadet wrong, but ends up getting sick from it.\n*In the 2007 Comedy Central TV show ''[[South Park]]'' episode \"Fantastic Easter Special\", a man named Professor Teabag (who knows of an Easter conspiracy) helps [[Stan Marsh]] and [[Kyle Broflovski]] escape from some ninjas by putting Peeps in the microwave, causing an explosion that destroys the mansion and killing both him and the ninjas.\n*In 2007-2008, Peeps featured prominently in the [[Vlogbrothers]] video blog series, primarily serving as comedic fodder for [https://nerdfighteria.info/article/1491 punishments].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of confectionery brands]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n*[http://www.marshmallowpeeps.com/ Peeps Official Website]\n*[http://www.marshmallowpeeps.org/pcn.html Tour of the Peeps Factory]\n*[http://www.peepresearch.org Peep Research]\n*[http://www.magnet.fsu.edu/education/community/slideshows/belljar/index.html How Atmospheric Pressure Affects Objects]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (audio slideshow, featuring Peeps, from the National High Magnetic Field Laboratory)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180805013919/http://powerofthepeep.com/ Peeps Documentary]\n*[http://www.salon.com/food/eyewitness_cook/index.html?story=/food/francis_lam/2010/04/03/toasted_peeps_brulee_recipe Peeps br\u00fbl\u00e9e! Like toasted marshmallows, but awesomer], Salon.com\n*[http://www.slate.com/id/2098422 Why Eat Peeps at Easter? How the marshmallow chicks found Jesus.], Slate.com\n\n{{Just Born}}\n\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1953]]\n[[Category:Brand name confectionery]]\n[[Category:Easter food]]\n[[Category:Just Born brands]]\n[[Category:Marshmallows]]\n", "name_user": "BattlePig101", "label": "safe", "comment": "changed chicks to ducks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peeps"}
{"title_page": "Per\u00ebndi", "text_new": "'''Per\u00ebndi''' ({{lang-sq-definite|Per\u00ebndia}}) is the [[Albanian language|Albanian]] word for [[God]], the [[sky]] and [[heaven]].{{Sfn|West|2007|p=240}}{{sfn|Gamkrelidze|1995|p=528}}{{sfn|Jakobson|1985|pp=6, 19-21}} Per\u00ebndi is thought to have been a [[Sky deity|sky]] and [[thunder god|thunder]] god in the [[Albanian mythology|Albanian pagan mythology]],{{sfn|Poghirc|1987|p=178}} and to have been worshiped by the [[Illyrians]] in antiquity.{{sfn|Treimer|1971|pp=31\u201333}} His name has been retained in the [[Albanian language]]\u2014along with the names [[Zojz (deity)#Epithet|Zot]] ([[Sky Father|Heavenly Father]]) and [[:wikt:hyj#Albanian|Hyj]] (Heavenly Glow)\u2014to refer to the [[Supreme Being]] after the spread of [[Christianity]].<ref name=\"Lurker150\">{{harvnb|Lurker|2005|p=150}}.</ref> Another archaic Albanian divine name of the sky and thunder god is [[Zojz (deity)|Zojz]], from [[Proto-Indo-European mythology|PIE]] [[Dyeus]] (Daylight-Sky-God).{{sfn|Mann|1952|pp=32}} In some of his attributes, Per\u00ebndi could be related to the weather and storm gods [[Shurdh]] and [[Verbt]],{{sfn|Treimer|1971|pp=31\u201333}} and to the mythological [[demigod]] [[drangue]].\n\n== Name and Etymology ==\nIn [[Albanian language|Albanian]], ''Per\u00ebnd\u00ed'' ([[definiteness|definite]]: ''Per\u00ebnd\u00eda'') is the [[name of God]], the [[sky]] and [[heaven]], and is used [[Capitalization|capitalized]] to refer to the [[Supreme Being]]. The plural indefinite form is ''per\u00ebnd\u00ed'' while the plural definite form is ''per\u00ebnd\u00edt\u00eb'', used uncapitalized to refer to the [[deities]]. Some [[Albanian dialects|dialectal]] alternative forms include: ''Perend\u00ed'', ''Perenn\u00ed'', ''Perund\u00ed'', ''Perud\u00ed'', ''Pernd\u00ed'' and ''Parand\u00ed''. Although the Albanian root ''per\u00ebndoj'' (\"to set of the sun\"), ultimately derived from [[Latin]] ''parentari'', the [[Passive voice|passive]] correlate of ''parentare'' (\"a sacrifice to the dead, to satisfy\"), has also been proposed,{{Sfn|Orel|1998|pp=315\u2013316}} the complex form ''Per\u00ebnd\u00ed'' is generally considered a compound of the roots ''per-en-'' (\"to strike') and ''-d\u00ed'' (\"sky, god\"):<ref>{{harvnb|West|2007|pp=242\u2013244}}; {{harvnb|Mallory|Adams|1997|pp=582\u2013583}}; {{harvnb|Jakobson|1985|pp=6, 19\u201321}}; {{harvnb|Treimer|1971|pp=31\u201333}}.</ref>\n\nThe first element belongs to the family of [[Proto-Indo-European mythology|Proto-Indo-European mythological]] names endowed with regular reflexes of the same root ''*per-'', \"to strike\", and a suffix ''-en/n-'' which has reflexes also in other [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] divine names like ''*peruh\u2093nos'' \"the one with the thunder stone\", or ''[[Perun|Perun/Perun\u016d]]'', the [[Slavic paganism|Slavic]] [[thunder god]], cf. ''[[Perkwunos|*''Perk<sup>w</sup>unos'']]'', the Proto-Indo-European [[Weather god|weather-god]].{{sfn|Jakobson|1985|pp=6, 19-21}}{{sfn|West|2007|pp=166\u2013167, 242-244}}{{Sfn|Mallory|Adams|1997|p=582\u2013583}} The non-enlarged root ''*per-'' is found also in the [[Hittite language|Hittite]] ''Peruna-'' (\"[[deity]]\" and \"holy cliff\"), in the [[Pamir languages|Pamir]] ''Perun'' (a war-god), cognate with [[Pashto]] ''P\u0113run\u0113'' (the name for the [[Pleiades]], cf. [[Avestan language|Avestan]] ''paoiriia\u0113in\u012b-''), and probably in [[Ancient Greek]] \u03ba\u03b5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c5\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2 (\"[[thunderbolt]]\") an epithet of [[Zeus]] and the name of a separate deity, which might have been a synonymic substitution for the prohibited form *\u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c5\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2. While velar enlargements are found in [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]] ''[[Perk\u016bnas]]'' (which could be the prohibited form of ''Per\u016bnas''), in [[Old Norse]] ''[[Fj\u00f6rgyn and Fj\u00f6rgynn|Fj\u00f6rgynn]]'', in [[Rigveda|Rigvedic]] ''[[Parjanya]]'' (god of storm and rain) and probably in [[Thracian language|Thracian]] ''Perkos/Perkon'' (\u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03ba\u03c9\u03bd/\u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2), a horseman hero.{{sfn|Jakobson|1985|pp=6, 19-21}}{{Sfn|Mallory|Adams|1997|p=582\u2013583}}{{Sfn|Jackson|2002|p=75\u201376}} Terms from the root ''*p\u00e9r-ur-'' and related to stone are also attested in [[Hittite language|Hitt.]] ''p\u0113ru'' (\"rock, cliff, boulder\"), [[Avestan|Aves.]] ''pauruuat\u0101'' (\"mountains\"), and [[Vedic Sanskrit|Skt]] ''p\u00e1rvata'' (\"rocky, cliff, mountain\").{{Sfn|Mallory|Adams|1997|p=582\u2013583}}{{Sfn|Kloekhorst|2008|p=669}}{{Sfn|Vaan|2018|pp=506\u2013507}}\n\nIn the [[Albanian language]], a word to refer to the lightning\u2014considered in [[Albanian folk beliefs|folk beliefs]] as the \"fire of the sky\"\u2014is ''shkreptim\u00eb'', a formation of ''[[:wikt:shkrep|shkrep]]'' meaning \"to flash, tone, to strike (till sparks fly off)\".{{sfn|Demiraj|1997|pp=363-364}} An association between strike, stones and fire, can be related to the observation that one can kindle fire by striking stones against each other. The act of [[Fire making|producing fire through a strike]]\u2014reflected also in the belief that fire is residual within the [[Oak|oak trees]] after the thunder-god strikes them\u2014indicates the potential of lightning in the [[Creation myth|myth of creation]].{{Sfn|Mallory|Adams|1997|p=582\u2013583}}\n\nThe second element ''d\u00ed/d\u00eda/dei'' (\"day, sky, deity\") derives from [[Proto-Indo-European language|PIE]] ''*[[Dyeus|Dy\u0113us]]'' (\"daylight-sky-god\"), which is found also in the archaic Albanian divine name of the sky and thunder god ''[[Zojz (deity)|Zojz]]'',{{sfn|Mann|1952|pp=32}} cognate with [[Messapian language|Messapian]] ''Zis'' and [[Greek mythology|Greek]] ''[[Zeus]]''.{{sfn|West|2007|pp=167, 242-244}} This element is thought to be contained also in another [[Albanian language|Albanain]] term for the [[Supreme Being]]: ''[[Zojz (deity)#Epithet|Zot]]'', considered to be derived from [[Proto-Albanian]] ''*d\u017aie\u0305u \u030a  a(t)t-'', an old compound for \"[[Sky father|heavenly father]]\", from [[Proto-Indo-European language|PIE]] [[:wikt:Reconstruction:Proto-Indo-European/dyew-|''*dyew-'']] (\"sky, heaven, bright\") + [[:wikt:Reconstruction:Proto-Indo-European/\u00e1tta|''*\u00e1tta'']] (\"father\"), thus a cognate with [[Proto-Indo-European mythology|PIE]] [[Dyeus|''*Dy\u1e17us ph\u2082t\u1e17r'']] and with its descendants: [[Illyrian mythology|Illyrian]] ''[[Deipaturos|Dei-p\u00e1trous]]'', [[Sanskrit]] \u0926\u094d\u092f\u094c\u0937\u094d\u092a\u093f\u0924\u0943 (''[[Dyaus|Dy\u00e1u\u1e63 Pit\u1e5b\u0301]]''), [[Proto-Italic]] ''*djous pat\u0113r'' (whence [[Latin]] ''[[Iuppiter]]''), [[Ancient Greek language|Ancient Greek]] \u0396\u03b5\u1fe6 \u03c0\u03ac\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1 (''[[Zeus|Ze\u00fb p\u00e1ter]]'').{{sfn|Demiraj|1997|pp=431-432}}{{sfn|Mann|1977|p=72}}{{sfn|Treimer|1971|p=32}}\n\n== Mythology ==\nIn [[Albanian mythology]], Per\u00ebndi is the consort of the love-goddess [[Prende]], comparable to [[Frigg]], [[Odin]]'s wife in [[Norse mythology]].{{sfn|Lambertz|1973|pp=455-509}}\n\n== Rituals ==\n=== Lightning and thunder-stones ===\nIn [[Albanian folk beliefs]] the [[lightning]] was regarded as the \"[[fire]] of the [[sky]]\" (''zjarri i qiellit'') and was considered the \"[[weapon]] of the deity\" (''arma/pushka e per\u00ebndis\u00eb''), indeed an Albanian word to refer to the lightning is ''[[:wikt:rrufe#Albanian|rrufeja]]'', related to the [[Thracian language|Thracian]] ''[[rhomphaia]]'', an ancient [[pole weapon]].{{sfn|Tirta|2004|pp=82, 406}} [[Albanians]] believed in the supreme powers of [[Thunderstone (folklore)|thunder-stones]] (''kokrra e rrufes\u00eb'' or ''guri i rej\u00ebs''), which were believed to be formed during [[lightning|lightning strikes]] and to be fallen from the [[sky]]. Thunder-stones were preserved in family life as important [[cult object]]s. It was believed that bringing them inside the house could bring [[good fortune]], prosperity and progress in people, in livestock and in agriculture, or that rifle bullets would not hit the owners of the thunder-stones.{{sfn|Tirta|2004|pp=82, 406}} A common practice was to hung a thunder-stone pendant on the body of the cattle or on the pregnant woman for good luck and to contrast the [[evil eye]].{{sfn|Tirta|2004|p=101}}\n\nIn [[Albanian culture]], the heaviest type of [[Oath|oath swearing]] ([[Albanian language|Alb.]] ''[[Besa (Albanian culture)|beja]] m\u00eb e r\u00ebnd\u00eb'') is taken by a thunder-stone \"which comes from the sky\" (''beja me gur/kok\u00ebrr reje/rrufeje q\u00eb vjen nga per\u00ebndia''). It was a very serious oath and people were afraid of it even though they were telling the truth.{{sfn|Tirta|2004|p=101}} The act of absolving himself of any allegation of theft was performed in the following way: the thunder-stone was taken in the left hand and was touched by the right hand saying:{{sfn|Tirta|2004|p=102}}\n{{Verse translation|lang=sq|P\u00ebr k\u00ebt\u00eb kok\u00ebrr rejet, nuk ta kam vjedh\u00eb as un\u00eb, as kush i shpis\u00eb sime e nuk e di se kush ta ka vjedh\u00eb! N\u00eb t\u00eb rrejsha, reja m\u00eb gjoft\u00eb!|I swear by this thunder-stone that I have not stolen it, nor anyone of my house and I don't know who stole it! If I lied to you, cloud strike me!}}\n\n=== Rainmaking ===\nPer\u00ebndi is especially [[Invocation|invoked]] by [[Albanians]] in [[incantation]]s and [[Rainmaking (ritual)|songs praying for rain]].{{sfn|Gamkrelidze|1995|p=528}} [[Rituals]] were performed in times of summer drought to make it rain, usually in June and July, but sometimes also in the spring months when there was severe drought. In different Albanian regions, for rainmaking purpose, people threw water upwards to make it subsequently fall to the ground in the form of rain. This was an imitative type of [[Incantation|magic practice]] with ritual songs.{{sfn|Tirta|2004|p=310}}\n\nIn [[Nowruz]] or in the Albanian [[Spring Day]] (''[[Dita e Ver\u00ebs]]''), in particular, in some villages of the region of [[Kurvelesh (region)|Kurvelesh]] in southern [[Albania]] people addressed the following prayer to the deity for plants and cattle:{{sfn|Tirta|2004|p=308}}\n{{Verse translation|lang=sq|O ''per\u00ebndi'', nepna shi n\u00eb v\u00ebrri!<br>T\u00eb b\u00ebhet misri dhe shelegu me bri!|Oh 'sky', give us rain on winter pastures!<br>So that corn and lamb will become horned!}}\n\nThe following is a hetero-homometric ritual song for rainmaking which includes also the figure of [[Dodola|Peperona]] (or ''Rona'', in other cases also ''Perperuga'', ''Dudula'' or the masculine form ''Dordolec'' or ''Durdulec''), a traditional mythical character of [[Balkans|Balkan]] folklore:{{sfn|Pipa|1978|p=58}}\n{{Verse translation|lang=sq|Rona-rona, Peperona,<br>bjer\u00eb shi nd\u00eb arat tona!<br>T\u00eb b\u00ebhet\u00eb thek\u00ebri<br>i gjat\u00eb gjer n\u00eb \u00e7ati,<br>gruri gjer n\u00eb per\u00ebndi,<br>ashtu edhe mis\u00ebri!|Rona-rona, Peperona,<br>pour rain on our fields!<br>So that oats will frow<br>as high as the roof,<br>wheat as high as the 'sky'.<br>and corn as well!}}\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Albanian folk beliefs]]\n*[[Illyrian religion]]\n*[[En (deity)]]\n*[[Zojz (deity)]]\n*[[Prende]]\n*[[Drangue]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite book|last=Demiraj|first=Bardhyl|title=Albanische Etymologien: Untersuchungen zum albanischen Erbwortschatz|series=Leiden Studies in Indo-European|volume=7|year=1997|language=de|place=Amsterdam, Atlanta|publisher=Rodopi|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gamkrelidze|first=Ivanov|title=Indo-European and the Indoeuropeans|publisher=Mouton de Gruyter|year=1995|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Jakobson|first=Roman|author-link=Roman Jakobson|editor=Stephen Rudy|title=Roman Jakobson: Selected Writings|volume=