ooks?id=3LJiAAAAMAAJ&q|ref=harv}}.\n*{{cite journal|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/282313685|last=Novik|first=Alexander|title=Lexicon of Albanian Mythology: Areal Studies in the Polylingual Region of Azov Sea|journal=Slavia Meridionalis|publisher=researchgate.net|volume=15|pages=261\u2013273|doi=10.11649/sm.2015.022|date=2015|access-date=2 January 2020}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pipa|first=Arshi|title=Albanian Folk Verse: Structure and Genre|publisher=O. Harrassowitz|year=1978|isbn=3878281196|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WCIHAQAAIAAJ&q|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Poghirc|first=Cicerone|title=The Encyclopedia of Religion|volume=1|chapter=Albanian Religion|editor=Mircea Eliade|place=New York|publisher=MacMillan Publishing Co|year=1987|pp=178\u2013180|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Tirta|first=Mark|title=Mitologjia nd\u00ebr shqiptar\u00eb|language=sq|editor=Petrit Bezhani|publisher=M\u00ebsonj\u00ebtorja|year=2004|place=Tirana|isbn=99927-938-9-9|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Treimer|first=Karl|editors=Henrik Bari\u0107, [[Albanological Institute of Pristina]]|title=Arhiv za Arbanasku starinu, jezik i etnologiju|volume=I|chapter=Zur R\u00fcckerschliessung der illyrischen G\u00f6tterwelt und ihre Bedeutung f\u00fcr die s\u00fcdslawische Philologie|pp=27\u201333|publisher=R. Trofenik|year=1971|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dTIBAAAAMAAJ&q|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=ecZ1DwAAQBAJ|title=Etymological Dictionary of Latin and the other Italic Languages|last=Vaan|first=Michiel de|date=2018-10-31|publisher=Leiden \u00b7 Boston, 2008|isbn=9789004167971|location=|language=en|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=West|first=M. L.|title=Indo-European Poetry and Myth|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2007|isbn=978-0-19-928075-9|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Per\u00ebndi}}\n[[Category:Albanian mythology]]\n[[Category:Albanian folklore]]\n[[Category:Thunder gods]]\n[[Category:Illyrian gods]]\n", "text_old": "'''Per\u00ebndi''' ({{lang-sq-definite|Per\u00ebndia}}) is the [[Albanian language|Albanian]] word for [[God]], the [[sky]] and [[heaven]].{{Sfn|West|2007|p=240}}{{sfn|Gamkrelidze|1995|p=528}}{{sfn|Jakobson|1985|pp=6, 19-21}} Per\u00ebndi is thought to have been a [[Sky deity|sky]] and [[thunder god|thunder]] god in the [[Albanian mythology|Albanian pagan mythology]],{{sfn|Poghirc|1987|p=178}} and to have been worshiped by the [[Illyrians]] in antiquity.{{sfn|Treimer|1971|pp=31\u201333}} His name has been retained in the [[Albanian language]]\u2014along with the names [[Zojz (deity)#Epithet|Zot]] ([[Sky Father|Heavenly Father]]) and [[:wikt:hyj#Albanian|Hyj]] (Heavenly Glow)\u2014to refer to the [[Supreme Being]] after the spread of [[Christianity]].<ref name=\"Lurker150\">{{harvnb|Lurker|2005|p=150}}.</ref> Another archaic Albanian divine name of the sky and thunder god is [[Zojz (deity)|Zojz]], from [[Proto-Indo-European mythology|PIE]] [[Dyeus]] (Daylight-Sky-God).{{sfn|Mann|1952|pp=32}} In some of his attributes, Per\u00ebndi could be related to the weather and storm gods [[Shurdh]] and [[Verbt]],{{sfn|Treimer|1971|pp=31\u201333}} and to the mythological [[demigod]] [[drangue]].\n\n== Name and Etymology ==\nIn [[Albanian language|Albanian]], ''Per\u00ebnd\u00ed'' ([[definiteness|definite]]: ''Per\u00ebnd\u00eda'') is the [[name of God]], the [[sky]] and [[heaven]], and is used [[Capitalization|capitalized]] to refer to the [[Supreme Being]]. The plural indefinite form is ''per\u00ebnd\u00ed'' while the plural definite form is ''per\u00ebnd\u00edt\u00eb'', used uncapitalized to refer to the [[deities]]. Some [[Albanian dialects|dialectal]] alternative forms include: ''Perend\u00ed'', ''Perenn\u00ed'', ''Perund\u00ed'', ''Perud\u00ed'', ''Pernd\u00ed'' and ''Parand\u00ed''. Although the Albanian root ''per\u00ebndoj'' (\"to set of the sun\"), ultimately derived from [[Latin]] ''parentari'', the [[Passive voice|passive]] correlate of ''parentare'' (\"a sacrifice to the dead, to satisfy\"), has also been proposed,{{Sfn|Orel|1998|pp=315\u2013316}} the complex form ''Per\u00ebnd\u00ed'' is generally considered a compound of the roots ''per-en-'' (\"to strike') and ''-d\u00ed'' (\"sky, god\"):<ref>{{harvnb|West|2007|p=242\u2013244}}; {{harvnb|Mallory|Adams|1997|p=582\u2013583}}; {{harvnb|Jakobson|1985|pp=6, 19\u201321}}; {{harvnb|Treimer|1971|pp=31\u201333}}.</ref>\n\nThe first element belongs to the family of [[Proto-Indo-European mythology|Proto-Indo-European mythological]] names endowed with regular reflexes of the same root ''*per-'', \"to strike\", and a suffix ''-en/n-'' which has reflexes also in other [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] divine names like ''*peruh\u2093nos'' \"the one with the thunder stone\", or ''[[Perun|Perun/Perun\u016d]]'', the [[Slavic paganism|Slavic]] [[thunder god]], cf. ''[[Perkwunos|*''Perk<sup>w</sup>unos'']]'', the Proto-Indo-European [[Weather god|weather-god]].{{sfn|Jakobson|1985|pp=6, 19-21}}{{sfn|West|2007|pp=166\u2013167, 242-244}}{{Sfn|Mallory|Adams|1997|p=582\u2013583}} The non-enlarged root ''*per-'' is found also in the [[Hittite language|Hittite]] ''Peruna-'' (\"[[deity]]\" and \"holy cliff\"), in the [[Pamir languages|Pamir]] ''Perun'' (a war-god), cognate with [[Pashto]] ''P\u0113run\u0113'' (the name for the [[Pleiades]], cf. [[Avestan language|Avestan]] ''paoiriia\u0113in\u012b-''), and probably in [[Ancient Greek]] \u03ba\u03b5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c5\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2 (\"[[thunderbolt]]\") an epithet of [[Zeus]] and the name of a separate deity, which might have been a synonymic substitution for the prohibited form *\u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c5\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2. While velar enlargements are found in [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]] ''[[Perk\u016bnas]]'' (which could be the prohibited form of ''Per\u016bnas''), in [[Old Norse]] ''[[Fj\u00f6rgyn and Fj\u00f6rgynn|Fj\u00f6rgynn]]'', in [[Rigveda|Rigvedic]] ''[[Parjanya]]'' (god of storm and rain) and probably in [[Thracian language|Thracian]] ''Perkos/Perkon'' (\u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03ba\u03c9\u03bd/\u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2), a horseman hero.{{sfn|Jakobson|1985|pp=6, 19-21}}{{Sfn|Mallory|Adams|1997|p=582\u2013583}}{{Sfn|Jackson|2002|p=75\u201376}} Terms from the root ''*p\u00e9r-ur-'' and related to stone are also attested in [[Hittite language|Hitt.]] ''p\u0113ru'' (\"rock, cliff, boulder\"), [[Avestan|Aves.]] ''pauruuat\u0101'' (\"mountains\"), and [[Vedic Sanskrit|Skt]] ''p\u00e1rvata'' (\"rocky, cliff, mountain\").{{Sfn|Mallory|Adams|1997|p=582\u2013583}}{{Sfn|Kloekhorst|2008|p=669}}{{Sfn|Vaan|2018|pp=506\u2013507}}\n\nIn the [[Albanian language]], a word to refer to the lightning\u2014considered in [[Albanian folk beliefs|folk beliefs]] as the \"fire of the sky\"\u2014is ''shkreptim\u00eb'', a formation of ''[[:wikt:shkrep|shkrep]]'' meaning \"to flash, tone, to strike (till sparks fly off)\".{{sfn|Demiraj|1997|pp=363-364}} An association between strike, stones and fire, can be related to the observation that one can kindle fire by striking stones against each other. The act of [[Fire making|producing fire through a strike]]\u2014reflected also in the belief that fire is residual within the [[Oak|oak trees]] after the thunder-god strikes them\u2014indicates the potential of lightning in the [[Creation myth|myth of creation]].{{Sfn|Mallory|Adams|1997|p=582\u2013583}}\n\nThe second element ''d\u00ed/d\u00eda/dei'' (\"day, sky, deity\") derives from [[Proto-Indo-European language|PIE]] ''*[[Dyeus|Dy\u0113us]]'' (\"daylight-sky-god\"), which is found also in the archaic Albanian divine name of the sky and thunder god ''[[Zojz (deity)|Zojz]]'',{{sfn|Mann|1952|pp=32}} cognate with [[Messapian language|Messapian]] ''Zis'' and [[Greek mythology|Greek]] ''[[Zeus]]''.{{sfn|West|2007|pp=167, 242-244}} This element is thought to be contained also in another [[Albanian language|Albanain]] term for the [[Supreme Being]]: ''[[Zojz (deity)#Epithet|Zot]]'', considered to be derived from [[Proto-Albanian]] ''*d\u017aie\u0305u \u030a  a(t)t-'', an old compound for \"[[Sky father|heavenly father]]\", from [[Proto-Indo-European language|PIE]] [[:wikt:Reconstruction:Proto-Indo-European/dyew-|''*dyew-'']] (\"sky, heaven, bright\") + [[:wikt:Reconstruction:Proto-Indo-European/\u00e1tta|''*\u00e1tta'']] (\"father\"), thus a cognate with [[Proto-Indo-European mythology|PIE]] [[Dyeus|''*Dy\u1e17us ph\u2082t\u1e17r'']] and with it's descendants: [[Illyrian mythology|Illyrian]] ''[[Deipaturos|Dei-p\u00e1trous]]'', [[Sanskrit]] \u0926\u094d\u092f\u094c\u0937\u094d\u092a\u093f\u0924\u0943 (''[[Dyaus|Dy\u00e1u\u1e63 Pit\u1e5b\u0301]]''), [[Proto-Italic]] ''*djous pat\u0113r'' (whence [[Latin]] ''[[Iuppiter]]''), [[Ancient Greek language|Ancient Greek]] \u0396\u03b5\u1fe6 \u03c0\u03ac\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1 (''[[Zeus|Ze\u00fb p\u00e1ter]]'').{{sfn|Demiraj|1997|pp=431-432}}{{sfn|Mann|1977|p=72}}{{sfn|Treimer|1971|p=32}}\n\n== Mythology ==\nIn [[Albanian mythology]], Per\u00ebndi is the consort of the love-goddess [[Prende]], comparable to [[Frigg]], [[Odin]]'s wife in [[Norse mythology]].{{sfn|Lambertz|1973|pp=455-509}}\n\n== Rituals ==\n=== Lightning and thunder-stones ===\nIn [[Albanian folk beliefs]] the [[lightning]] was regarded as the \"[[fire]] of the [[sky]]\" (''zjarri i qiellit'') and was considered the \"[[weapon]] of the deity\" (''arma/pushka e per\u00ebndis\u00eb''), indeed an Albanian word to refer to the lightning is ''[[:wikt:rrufe#Albanian|rrufeja]]'', related to the [[Thracian language|Thracian]] ''[[rhomphaia]]'', an ancient [[pole weapon]].{{sfn|Tirta|2004|pp=82, 406}} [[Albanians]] believed in the supreme powers of [[Thunderstone (folklore)|thunder-stones]] (''kokrra e rrufes\u00eb'' or ''guri i rej\u00ebs''), which were believed to be formed during [[lightning|lightning strikes]] and to be fallen from the [[sky]]. Thunder-stones were preserved in family life as important [[cult object]]s. It was believed that bringing them inside the house could bring [[good fortune]], prosperity and progress in people, in livestock and in agriculture, or that rifle bullets would not hit the owners of the thunder-stones.{{sfn|Tirta|2004|pp=82, 406}} A common practice was to hung a thunder-stone pendant on the body of the cattle or on the pregnant woman for good luck and to contrast the [[evil eye]].{{sfn|Tirta|2004|p=101}}\n\nIn [[Albanian culture]], the heaviest type of [[Oath|oath swearing]] ([[Albanian language|Alb.]] ''[[Besa (Albanian culture)|beja]] m\u00eb e r\u00ebnd\u00eb'') is taken by a thunder-stone \"which comes from the sky\" (''beja me gur/kok\u00ebrr reje/rrufeje q\u00eb vjen nga per\u00ebndia''). It was a very serious oath and people were afraid of it even though they were telling the truth.{{sfn|Tirta|2004|p=101}} The act of absolving himself of any allegation of theft was performed in the following way: the thunder-stone was taken in the left hand and was touched by the right hand saying:{{sfn|Tirta|2004|p=102}}\n{{Verse translation|lang=sq|P\u00ebr k\u00ebt\u00eb kok\u00ebrr rejet, nuk ta kam vjedh\u00eb as un\u00eb, as kush i shpis\u00eb sime e nuk e di se kush ta ka vjedh\u00eb! N\u00eb t\u00eb rrejsha, reja m\u00eb gjoft\u00eb!|I swear by this thunder-stone that I have not stolen it, nor anyone of my house and I don't know who stole it! If I lied to you, cloud strike me!}}\n\n=== Rainmaking ===\nPer\u00ebndi is especially [[Invocation|invoked]] by [[Albanians]] in [[incantation]]s and [[Rainmaking (ritual)|songs praying for rain]].{{sfn|Gamkrelidze|1995|p=528}} [[Rituals]] were performed in times of summer drought to make it rain, usually in June and July, but sometimes also in the spring months when there was severe drought. In different Albanian regions, for rainmaking purpose, people threw water upwards to make it subsequently fall to the ground in the form of rain. This was an imitative type of [[Incantation|magic practice]] with ritual songs.{{sfn|Tirta|2004|p=310}} \n\nIn [[Nowruz]] or in the Albanian [[Spring Day]] (''[[Dita e Ver\u00ebs]]''), in particular, in some villages of the region of [[Kurvelesh (region)|Kurvelesh]] in southern [[Albania]] people addressed the following prayer to the deity for plants and cattle:{{sfn|Tirta|2004|p=308}}\n{{Verse translation|lang=sq|O ''per\u00ebndi'', nepna shi n\u00eb v\u00ebrri!<br>T\u00eb b\u00ebhet misri dhe shelegu me bri!|Oh 'sky', give us rain on winter pastures!<br>So that corn and lamb will become horned!}}\n\nThe following is a hetero-homometric ritual song for rainmaking which includes also the figure of [[Dodola|Peperona]] (or ''Rona'', in other cases also ''Perperuga'', ''Dudula'' or the masculine form ''Dordolec'' or ''Durdulec''), a traditional mythical character of [[Balkans|Balkan]] folklore:{{sfn|Pipa|1978|p=58}}\n{{Verse translation|lang=sq|Rona-rona, Peperona,<br>bjer\u00eb shi nd\u00eb arat tona!<br>T\u00eb b\u00ebhet\u00eb thek\u00ebri<br>i gjat\u00eb gjer n\u00eb \u00e7ati,<br>gruri gjer n\u00eb per\u00ebndi,<br>ashtu edhe mis\u00ebri!|Rona-rona, Peperona,<br>pour rain on our fields!<br>So that oats will frow<br>as high as the roof,<br>wheat as high as the 'sky'.<br>and corn as well!}}\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Albanian folk beliefs]]\n*[[Illyrian religion]]\n*[[En (deity)]]\n*[[Zojz (deity)]]\n*[[Prende]]\n*[[Drangue]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite book|last=Demiraj|first=Bardhyl|title=Albanische Etymologien: Untersuchungen zum albanischen Erbwortschatz|series=Leiden Studies in Indo-European|volume=7|year=1997|language=de|place=Amsterdam, Atlanta|publisher=Rodopi|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gamkrelidze|first=Ivanov|title=Indo-European and the Indoeuropeans|publisher=Mouton de Gruyter|year=1995|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Jakobson|first=Roman|author-link=Roman Jakobson|editor=Stephen Rudy|title=Roman Jakobson: Selected Writings|volume=VII: Contributions to Comparative Mythology: Studies in L